---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<Layout 
  title="Dispensary Security Requirements | Maine Dispensary Guide" 
  description="Complete guide to security requirements for Maine cannabis dispensaries. Includes surveillance, alarm systems, access control, and compliance requirements."
  heroImage="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1557597774-9d273605dfa9?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=1200&h=400"
>
  <article>
    <div class="article-header">
      <h1>Security Requirements</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Understanding Maine's dispensary <a href="/guides/maine-dispensary-security/">security requirements</a> and best practices</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Overview</h2>
      <p>Maine requires comprehensive security systems for all cannabis dispensaries. These requirements are designed to protect inventory, employees, and customers while ensuring compliance with state regulations.</p>
    </section>

    <Callout title="Peace of Mind" type="success">
      A robust security plan is more than just a regulatory box to check—it's the shield that protects your hard work, your team, and your community. When you know your shop is secure, you can sleep soundly and focus your energy on what you love: providing exceptional products and service.
    </Callout>

    <section>
      <h2>Video Surveillance</h2>
...
        <li>Budget $30K-75K for security systems</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="further-reading">
      <h2>Further Reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.maine.gov/dafs/ocp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Maine Office of Cannabis Policy (OCP)</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.maine.gov/dafs/ocp/adult-use/security" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">OCP Security Guidelines</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="faq">
      <h2>Extreme FAQ: Security Edition</h2>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Does my security safe need to be fireproof?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Maine OCP requires that storage safes meet specific fire resistance standards—typically a minimum of one-hour fire rating. This protects your cash and valuable inventory from both theft AND fire damage. Expect to pay $2,000-$10,000 for a compliant safe depending on size and features.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>How many cameras are required per square foot?</summary>
        <p>Maine doesn't specify an exact ratio, but requirements include: all entry/exit points, point-of-sale areas, vault/safe locations, storage rooms, and anywhere inventory is handled. For a typical 1,500 sq ft dispensary, plan for 12-16 cameras minimum. The key is complete coverage with no blind spots.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I use wireless cameras?</summary>
        <p>Not recommended. Wired cameras are the standard for cannabis security because they're more reliable and harder to disable. Wireless systems can experience signal interference, battery failures, and are more vulnerable to tampering. Hardwired systems with battery backup are the industry standard.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What happens if my security system goes down?</summary>
        <p>You must notify OCP immediately and follow their incident protocol. Extended outages (typically more than 8 hours) may require temporary closure until systems are restored. Many operators maintain backup systems and 24/7 monitoring to prevent any gap in coverage. Insurance policies often require specific backup procedures.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Do I need armed guards?</summary>
        <p>Maine doesn't require armed guards, but some situations warrant them. High-value locations, high-crime areas, or very large operations may benefit from security personnel. Unarmed guards are more common and can provide a visible deterrent. Many operators find that well-trained staff and robust systems reduce the need for guards.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>How long must I keep security footage?</summary>
        <p>Maine requires minimum 90 days of video retention, but many operators keep 6-12 months. Camera resolution matters—higher resolution means more storage costs. Plan for significant cloud or local storage capacity. Budget $500-$2,000/month for secure off-site video storage.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I have a security system in my parking lot?</summary>
        <p>Yes, and it's highly recommended. Parking lot coverage is often required by OCP and definitely expected by insurers. Exterior cameras should capture license plates and provide clear views of the property perimeter. Consider motion-activated lighting as well.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What about employees stealing product?</summary>
        <p>This is why comprehensive interior surveillance is critical. Cameras must cover all areas where product is stored, handled, or transported. Many operators also implement inventory tracking systems, random bag/chest searches, and policies requiring employee bags to be checked. Prevention is far cheaper than loss.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

    <section class="disclaimer">
      <p><em>Requirements subject to change. Verify current Maine Office of Cannabis Policy requirements.</em></p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>

